    & Before you speak, let your words pass through {(bold "three gates")}.
    - At the first gate, ask yourself, is it {(bold "true")}.
    - At the second gate ask, is it {(bold "necessary")}.
    - At the third gate ask, is it {(bold "kind")}.
    * Arguments Ranking
    & The arguments rankings are taken from {(link "http://slatestarcodex.com/2018/05/08/varieties-of-argumentative-experience/" "Scott Alexander")}.
    | ●●●●● | {(bold "High-level generators")} | Disagreements that remain when everyone understands exactly what's being argued, and agrees on what all the evidence says, but have vague and hard-to-define reasons for disagreeing.
    | ●●●●○ | {(bold "Operationalizing")}      | Where both parties understand they're in a cooperative effort to fix exactly what they're arguing about.
    | ●●●○○ | {(bold "Survey of evidence")}    | Not trying to devastate the other person with a mountain of facts and start looking at the studies and arguments on both sides and figuring out what kind of complex picture they paint.
    | ●●●○○ | {(bold "Disputing definitions")} | Argument hinges on the meaning of words, or whether something counts as a member of a category or not.
    | ●●○○○ | {(bold "Single Studies")}        | Better than scattered facts, proving they at least looked into the issue formally.
    | ●●○○○ | {(bold "Demands for rigor")}     | Attempts to demand that an opposing argument be held to such strict standards that nothing could possibly clear the bar.
    | ●○○○○ | {(bold "Single Facts")}          | One fact, which admittedly does support their argument, but presented as if it solves the debate in and of itself.
    | ●○○○○ | {(bold "Gotchas")}               | Short claims that purport to be devastating proof that one side can't possibly be right.
    | ○○○○○ | {(bold "Social shaming")}        | A demand for listeners to place someone outside the boundary of whom deserve to be heard.
    λ (match (database:select "glossary") ("arguments"))
    * Responses Ranking
    & The responses rankings are taken from {(link "http://www.paulgraham.com/disagree.html" "Paul Graham")}.
    | ●●●●●● | {(bold "Central point")}      | Commit to refute explicitly the central point.
    | ●●●●●○ | {(bold "Refutation")}         | Argue a conflicting passage, explain why it's mistaken.
    | ●●●●○○ | {(bold "Counterargument")}    | Contradict with added reasoning or evidence.
    | ●●●○○○ | {(bold "Contradiction")}      | State the opposing case, what.
    | ●●○○○○ | {(bold "Responding to Tone")} | Responding to the author's tone, how.
    | ●○○○○○ | {(bold "Ad Hominem")}         | Attacking the author directly, who.
    λ (match (database:select "glossary") ("responses"))
