LIETAL
  UNDE : Language
  BREF : {(link)} is an experimental {(link "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constructed_language" "synthetic language")}.
  ICON : M60,240 a30,-30 0 0,1 30,-30 l150,0 M90,195 a30,-30 0 0,1 30,-30 l90,0 M120,150 a30,-30 0 0,1 30,-30 l30,0 M195,120 l45,0 M225,165 l15,0 M150,105 a30,-30 0 0,1 30,-30 l60,0
  BODY
    & {(bold "Lietal")} is written from left to right with implicit neutrality, singularity and at the present tense.
    & For the most part, its {(bold "6 vowels and 9 consonants")} are voiced similarly to their {(link "English")} equivalents. Sustained vowels, such as "{(ital "ä")}", are indicated with the trema. The Lietal "{(ital "e")}" is very short, a barely audible junction between two consonants.
    | I /i/ | l{(bold "ea")}ves      | Y /ɨ/ | journ{(bold "ey")}     | E /e/ | n{(bold "e")}ver
    | A /ə/ | hex{(bold "a")}gram    | O /ɔ/ | aut{(bold "o")}mobile  | U /u/ | n{(bold "ew")}
    | K [k] | {(bold "k")}iss        | T [t] | ti{(bold "t")}le       | D [d] | {(bold "d")}evice
    | R [ʁ] | retu{(bold "r")}n      | S [s] | {(bold "s")}ymphony    | L [l] | {(bold "l")}igature
    | J [ʐ] | mena{(bold "g")}erie   | V [v] | {(bold "v")}ideo       | F [f] | {(bold "f")}estival
    * Phonology
    & Building words from Lietal's phonemes is called {(bold "Childspeak")}. It makes for long rhythmical and syllabic words, its main usage is in loan words and to express of emphasis or exclamation. This documentation uses the phonetically denser form {(bold "Adultspeak")} where patterns of duplicated consonants and vowels are condensed.
    | CVCV | {(bold "lili")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "lili")} | {(bold "falili")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "falili")} | {(bold "fafalili")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "fafalili")}
    | CVCv | {(bold "lila")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "lila")} | {(bold "falila")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "falila")} | {(bold "fafolila")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "fafolila")}
    | CVcV | {(bold "viki")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "viki")} | {(bold "faviki")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "faviki")} | {(bold "fafoviki")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "fafoviki")}
    | CVcv | {(bold "lika")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "lika")} | {(bold "falika")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "falika")} | {(bold "favolika")} > {(lietal:adultspeak "favolika")}
    & A single syllable of childspeak is reversed, so "vo" becomes <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "vo")}</b>. A sequence of consonant, like "lyla", is condensed into <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "lyla")}</b>. A sequence of vowels, like "lara", is condensed into <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "lara")}</b>, in which an additional short "{(ital "e")}" is added inbetween the two consonants.
    & When no sequence of consonants or vowels are present, an extra vowel is also added between the consonants, so "lira", is transformed into <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "lira")}</b>.
    * Morphology
    & Lietal words are built from the combination of the {(bold "9 Elementary Particles")}, and each one contains a {(ital "consonant & a vowel")}.
    | &nbsp;          | {(bold "Directional")}               | {(bold "Perspectival")}              | {(bold "Mechanical")}
    | {(bold "Objective")}   | Ky <b>{(lietal:lien "ky")}</b>-type | Ty <b>{(lietal:lien "ty")}</b>-type | Dy <b>{(lietal:lien "dy")}</b>-type
    | {(bold "Observative")} | Ry <b>{(lietal:lien "ry")}</b>-type | Sy <b>{(lietal:lien "sy")}</b>-type | Ly <b>{(lietal:lien "ly")}</b>-type
    | {(bold "Subjective")}  | Jy <b>{(lietal:lien "jy")}</b>-type | Vy <b>{(lietal:lien "vy")}</b>-type | Fy <b>{(lietal:lien "fy")}</b>-type
    & {(bold "Words are not created, but found")} among the permutations of the nine elementary particles, making for a total of {(bold "27 Elementary Constructs")}. These elementary constructs can be combined with each other, to create more complex ideas.
    | &nbsp;          | {(bold "Directional")}          | {(bold "Perspectival")}         | {(bold "Mechanical")}
    | {(bold "Objective")}   | <b>KY {(lietal:lien "ky")}</b> | <b>TY {(lietal:lien "ty")}</b> | <b>DY {(lietal:lien "dy")}</b>
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ki")} {(lietal:lien "ki")}  | • {(bold "Ti")} {(lietal:lien "ti")}  | • {(bold "Di")} {(lietal:lien "di")}
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ka")} {(lietal:lien "ka")}  | • {(bold "Ta")} {(lietal:lien "ta")}  | • {(bold "Da")} {(lietal:lien "da")}
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ko")} {(lietal:lien "ko")}  | • {(bold "To")} {(lietal:lien "to")}  | • {(bold "Do")} {(lietal:lien "do")}
    | {(bold "Observative")} | <b>RY {(lietal:lien "ry")}</b> | <b>SY {(lietal:lien "sy")}</b> | <b>LY {(lietal:lien "ly")}</b>
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ri")} {(lietal:lien "ri")}  | • {(bold "Si")} {(lietal:lien "si")}  | • {(bold "Li")} {(lietal:lien "li")}
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ra")} {(lietal:lien "ra")}  | • {(bold "Sa")} {(lietal:lien "sa")}  | • {(bold "La")} {(lietal:lien "la")}
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ro")} {(lietal:lien "ro")}  | • {(bold "So")} {(lietal:lien "so")}  | • {(bold "Lo")} {(lietal:lien "lo")}
    | {(bold "Subjective")}  | <b>JY {(lietal:lien "jy")}</b> | <b>VY {(lietal:lien "vy")}</b> | <b>FY {(lietal:lien "fy")}</b>
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ji")} {(lietal:lien "ji")}  | • {(bold "Vi")} {(lietal:lien "vi")}  | • {(bold "Fi")} {(lietal:lien "fi")}
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Ja")} {(lietal:lien "ja")}  | • {(bold "Va")} {(lietal:lien "va")}  | • {(bold "Fa")} {(lietal:lien "fa")}
    | &nbsp;          | • {(bold "Jo")} {(lietal:lien "jo")}  | • {(bold "Vo")} {(lietal:lien "vo")}  | • {(bold "Fo")} {(lietal:lien "fo")}
    & For example, <b>{(lietal:enli "to show")}</b>(to show), is built of the elementary constructs <b>{(lietal:enli "to see")}</b>(to see) and <b>{(lietal:enli "outward")}</b>(outward). The word for dictionary is <b>{(tc (lietal:enli "dictionary"))}</b>, which literally means {(ital "a collection of words")}, built from <b>{(lietal:enli "together")}</b>(together) and <b>{(lietal:enli "word")}</b>(word).
    & The <b>leading syllable determines a word's type</b>, for example, <b>{(lietal:enli "to show")}</b> inherits the action-type from <b>{(lietal:enli "to see")}</b>(to see), therefore anything that begins with <b>{(lietal:enli "to see")}</b> can be assumed to be an action word relating to sight.
    | {(bold "fo")}     | {(lietal:adultspeak "fo")}     | {(lietal:lien "fo")}      | {(bold "la")}     | {(lietal:adultspeak "la")}     | {(lietal:lien "la")}
    | {(bold "fori")}   | {(lietal:adultspeak "fori")}   | {(lietal:lien "fori")}    | {(bold "laro")}   | {(lietal:adultspeak "laro")}   | {(lietal:lien "laro")}
    | {(bold "foriko")} | {(lietal:adultspeak "foriko")} | {(lietal:lien "foriko")}  | {(bold "laroko")} | {(lietal:adultspeak "laroko")} | {(lietal:lien "laroko")}
