ASODEKY
  UNDE : Lietal
  BREF : The {(link)}, is the advanced {(link "Lietal")} language guide.
  BODY
    & The order of words {(bold "follows the table of Elementary Particles")}. In a typical sentence, {(bold "traverse")}-type("k") words will be found at the beginning, and {(bold "action")}-type("f") words, at the end.
    & The following sequence of letters is the normal flow of a sentence, {(bold "when a sentence must break the word order, commas are used")}. Notice the word order in the following sentence, and specifically how a comma is used to join two sentences that would normaly break the word order.
    | K | T | D | R | S | L | J | V | F
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "soon" "home" "to go"))}</b>, "I am going home soon."
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "library" "from" "," "home" "to go")}</b>, "I am going home, from the library."
    * Reference
    & {(bold "Traverse")}-type words are meant to navigate a hierarchy, and are often used at the beginning of a sentence. To be {(ital "at a place")}, in Lietal, is made explicit with the "{(lietal:enli "location")}" marker, like <b>{(lietal:enli "location" "school")}</b> for "{(ital "at school")}", and <b>{(lietal:enli "child" "school")}</b> for "{(ital "in school")}".
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "location" "house" "," "soon" "we" "to leave"))}</b>, "We are at the house, we are leaving soon".
    & {(bold "State")}-type words are meant to define the state of existence of something. Where <b>{(lietal:enli "psychologic")}</b> will speak of the idea, or concept of a thing, <b>{(lietal:enli "phisionomic")}</b> will speak of the shape of a thing, and <b>{(lietal:enli "physic")}</b> will speak of the thing itself. The difference can be better explained when used in an action, or with the examples: <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "fiti")}</b>({(lietal:lien "fiti")}), <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "fita")}</b>({(lietal:lien "fita")}) & <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "fito")}</b>({(lietal:lien "fito")}).
    & {(bold "Scale")}-type words are used to define things that are made <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "do")}</b>(machines, products), from life-itself <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "da")}</b>(fauna, flora) and from things that makes life <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "di")}</b>(time, space).
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "home" "future" "to be"))}</b>, "I will be at home"
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "you" "future" "to see"))}</b>, "I will see you later"
    & {(bold "Direction")}-type words are used to change the attributes of a concept, to transition toward something other or to create a conceptual arrow.
    & {(bold "Relation")}-type words will most often be used as particles to create the equivalence of English particles "{(ital "and")}" and "{(ital "with")}", or to create enumerations.
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "between" "you" "i"))}</b>, "Between you and I"
    & {(bold "Counter")}-type words are often used to create subject pronouns, or parts of larger concepts like months in a year, or an item in a series. A sentence, by default, is expected to be {(bold "at the 1st person")}, if a pronoun has not already been declared, pronouns are often omitted when possible. The basic Lietal singular pronouns are <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "lari")}</b>({(lietal:lien "lari")}), <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "lara")}</b>({(lietal:lien "lara")}), <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "laro")}</b>({(lietal:lien "laro")}). The basic plural pronouns are <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "liri")}</b>({(lietal:lien "liri")}), <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "lira")}</b>({(lietal:lien "lira")}), <b>{(lietal:adultspeak "liro")}</b>({(lietal:lien "liro")}).
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "i" "to go"))}</b>, "I am going"
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "they" "to go"))}</b>, "They are going"
    & {(bold "Modality")}-type words are usually used to create words like "couldn't", "could", "must", or <b>{(lietal:enli "could not")}</b>, <b>{(lietal:enli "could")}</b>, <b>{(lietal:enli "must")}</b>.
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "must" "where" "to go"))}</b>, "Where must I go?"
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "could" "who" "to be"))}</b>, "Who might you be?"
    & {(bold "Alignment")}-type words are used to express a standing on a specific topic, for example, to express that something is wanted or not. Many of the daily expressions of greetings are also created from <b>{(lietal:enli "positive")}</b>, for example, <b>{(lietal:enli "welcome")}</b>(welcome) is made from <b>{(lietal:enli "positive")}</b>(positive) & <b>{(lietal:enli "inward")}</b>(inward). This pattern can be expanded to mean things like <b>{(lietal:enli "well done")}</b>(well done), or even <b>{(lietal:enli "health")}</b>(health).
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "welcome" "how"))}?</b>, "Hello, how are you?"
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "bye" "," "soon" "to see")}!</b>, "Good Bye, see you soon!"
    & {(bold "Action")}-type words are usually used at the end of a sentence and are generally built from the {(ital "fy")} family. The sentence "I take the book home" is translated to <b>{(lietal:enli "child" "book" "home" "to take")}</b>, following the {(code "K T F")} structure. Or another example, "I give you the book", could be translated to <b>{(lietal:enli "child" "book" "you" "to give")}</b>, following the {(code "K T L F")} structure.
    - <b>Lietal {(lietal:enli "possible" "to understand")}?</b>, "Can you understand Lietal?".
    - <b>{(cc (lietal:enli "child" "home" "to welcome"))}</b>, "I welcome you home".
JAPANESE
  UNDE : Language
  BREF : The {(link)} page is a collection of {(bold "Japanese study notes")}.
  ICON : M60,90 l180,0 l0,90 a-60,60 0 0,1 -60,60 M120,60 l0,60 a-60,120 0 0,1 -60,120
  BODY
    & This is an edited version on {(bold "Tad Perry")}'s "{(ital "Quick & Dirty Guide to Japanese")}".
    & I have formatted this guide to be a study tool prior to moving to {(link "Japan")} a few years ago, it requires the knowledge to {(bold "read Hiragana, Katakana and basic kanjis")}.
    * Sentence Word Order
    & In general, the main verb is found at the end of the sentence. Subjects are shown in grey as they are very often omitted. The preposition follows the noun, it is more properly called a postposition(て、に、お、は). They are not independent words but particles by which the case of nouns is determined.
    @ I'm going to give a present to my teacher tomorrow at school.
    | <span style='color:#999'>Subject</span>  | {(bold "Time")}   | {(bold "Place")}    | {(bold "Indirect")} | {(bold "Object")}      | {(bold "Action Verb")}
    | <span style='color:#999'>私は</span>      | 明日   | 学校で     | 先生に    | プレゼントを   | <b>上げます</b>
    | <span style='color:#999'>わたくしは</span> | あした  | がっこうで | せんせいに  | ぷれぜんとを | <b>あげます</b>
    * Particles
    - Use は after the subject, if a {(bold "new subject is introduced")} where another had been previously understood. If a subject is understood, but for some reason not deleted use が, or nothing.
    - Use に to indicate a specific points in {(bold "time")}, a word like "tomorrow"（明日） can only be understood by context and does not need the particle added. Like "In October", or 十月に — or like "On March 3rd", or 三月三日に. <b>Indirect objects</b> are also followed by に, similar to the english expression "to you", as seen in the following sentence "I'm going to give this book to you.", or この本をあなたに上げる.
    - Use で after the {(bold "place")} you do something or the {(bold "thing")} you use to do something. For example, "Going by car", is 車で行く.
    - Use を after a noun to declare an {(bold "object")}, as seen in the following sentence "I'm reading a book", or 本を読んでいる.
    - Use も to <b>add extra info</b> on top of what has already been declared, not unlike the english word "too", as in "me too". For example, "I'm going too", is ぼくも行く.
    - Use の to indicate {(bold "possession")} after an object, similarly to the english possession particle "'s", as in "Alex's". For example, "This is my book" is これはぼくの本です.
    - Use か at the end of a sentence to create a {(bold "question")}, as in "What time is it?", or 何時ですか? Or, between {(bold "choices")}, each choice is also followed by か. As in "Today or tomorrow?", or 今日か明日？
    - Use ね after a verb to create a sort of {(bold "agreement")} with the listener, not unlike the english expression "isn't?", in "It's fun isn't it?", or たのうしいですね.
    * Nouns
    & Nouns have no inflection to indicate singularity or plurality, for example, こども means both child and children. When wishing to show the plural of a noun, an indicator such as ーら、ーたち are attached, as in こどもたち, meaning children. Generally, the plural distinction is not made, but is left to be understood from the context.
    * Adjectives
    & Adjectives always end in あい, いい, うい or おい, never in えい that would be a noun. Basically, you replace the ending い to inflect.
    | 優しい | やさしい | It's nice
    | 優しくない | やさしくない | It's not nice
    | 優しかった | やさしかった | It was nice
    | 優しかったら | やさしかったら | If it's nice
    * Verbs
    & The ーる verbs that end in like たべる and いれる. There is always an い or an え before ーる. For these verbs, everything is done by dropping or replacing ーる with something else.
    | {(ital "食べ")}る | Eating
    | {(ital "食べ")}ます | (Polite)
    | {(ital "食べ")}て | Gerund
    | {(ital "食べ")}た | I ate it.
    | {(ital "食べ")}やすい | This is easy to eat.
    | {(ital "食べ")}たら | If I/someone eats.
    | {(ital "食べ")}たり | I did things like eating
    | {(ital "食べ")}れば | If I/someone eats.
    | {(ital "食べ")}よう | Let's eat.
    | {(ital "食べ")}ろ | Eat dammit!
    | {(ital "食べ")}ないでよ | Don't eat that!
    | {(ital "食べ")}られる | I can eat
    | {(ital "食べ")}られるない | I can't eat this!
    | {(ital "食べ")}させる | Make someone do
    | {(ital "食べ")}させない　で　よ | Don't make me eat this!
    | {(ital "食べ")}させられる | Be made to eat
    & These verbs end in う, く, ぐ, ぶ, む, ぬ, す, つ, or ある・いる・うる・える・おる. Typically you drop ーう and add something else. The problem is that there might be a phonetic change, such as when は becomes ぱ, or た becomes だ.
    | {(bold "talk")}  | はな   | 話す  | 話して | 話しった  | 話したら   | 話せ | 話さない | 話せる
    | {(bold "walk")}  | きく   | きく　 | きいて  | 聞いた   | 聞いたら | 聞け | 聞かない  | 聞ける
    | {(bold "swim")}  | およぐ  | 泳ぐ | 泳いでる | 泳いだ   | 泳いだら | 泳げ | 泳がない | 泳げる
    | {(bold "call")}  | よび   | 呼ぶ　 | 呼んで  | 呼んだ   | 呼んだら | 呼べ  | 呼ばない  | 呼べる
    | {(bold "drink")} | ぬも   | 飲む　 | 飲んで  | 飲んだ   | 飲んだら | 飲め  | 飲まない  | 飲める
    | {(bold "die")}   | しぬ   | 死ぬ　 | 死んで  | 死んだ   | 死んだら | 死ね  | 死なない  | 死ねる
    | {(bold "make")}  | つくる | 作る　 | 作って | つ作った  | 作ったら | 作れ | 作らない | 作れる
    | {(bold "wait")}  | まて   | 待つ　 | 待って  | 待った   | 待ったら |  | 待たない | 待てる
    | {(bold "pay")}   | はらう  | 払う | 払って | 払った  | 払ったら | 払え | 払わない | 払える
    & There are some ーう verbs that end in ーる like ある(to be), おる(to break) and うる(to sell) are ーう verbs as they do not have an い or え sound before ーる.
    & If you see one that ends in ーいる or ーえる, and ーう changes to add ーます, or the "t" doubles to get a gerund (入る「はいる」　＞　入って「はいって」), then you're dealing with an ーう verb.
    & Most books say that there are only two irregular verbs in all of Japanese: する and 来る「くる」. Those you have to memorize separately, but they kind of make sense when you look at them.
    | 来る | will come                        | する　 | will do
    | 来て | come here                        | して　 | do this
    | 来た | someone came                     | した　 | someone did
    | 来たら | if someone comes                | したら | if someone does
    | 来たり | do things like come             | したり　 | do things like doing
    | 来れば | if someone comes                | すれば | if someone does
    | 来よう | let's come                      | しよう | let's do
    | 来い | come here you!                   | しろ | do this dammit!
    | 来ない | won't come, or doesn't come    | しない | won't do, or doesn't do
    | 来らせる | can come                      | できる | can do
    | 来させる | make someone come             | させる | make someone do
    | 来られる | ?                             | される | be done
    | 来させられる | be made to come by someone  | させられる | be made to do by someone
    & A trick to remember する conjugations is that they often match what you would get if you conjugated a lone す.　Like はな<b>した</b>, はな<b>せる</b>, はな<b>させる</b>.
